<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="586" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1187,1410,1473]" box="[151,739,1410,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,739,1410,1437]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,739,1410,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
Key to amber genera of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1881" box="[630,739,1410,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Erotinae">Erotinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1187,1410,1473]" box="[151,1187,1447,1473]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">The five currently known Erotinae amber genera may be distinguished by the following key.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="586" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" box="[151,1436,1516,1538]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1516,1538]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
1. Pronotum with rhomboidal median areole (as in 
<figureCitation box="[692,791,1516,1538]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,184,1597]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[151,1436,181,1603]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A—J. Morphology of the extant Erotinae. A—Eropterus sp., Japan, general appearance, dorsal view; B–D— elytron, humeral part. B—Eropterus sp., Japan; C—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan; D—Lopheros sp., Japan. E— G—Pronotum. E—Eropterus trilineatus (Melsheimer), USA, dorsal view; F—Lopheros sp., Japan; G—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan. H– J General appearance, dorsal view. H—Helcophorus miniatus Fairmaire, Himalayas; I—Greenarus belokobylskyi Kazantsev, Vietnam; J—Laterialis sanguinea Kazantsev, China. Eocene Erotini. K—Protolopheros hoffeinsorum Kazantsev, Baltic amber (photo from Kazantsev, 2013). Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655708/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Figs 2G–J</figureCitation>
)...................................... (
<taxonomicName box="[1281,1412,1516,1538]" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" rank="tribe" tribe="Dictyopterini">Dictyopterini</taxonomicName>
) 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" box="[151,1436,1545,1567]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1545,1567]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
- Pronotum with cross-like structure of pronotal carinae (
<figureCitation box="[758,887,1545,1567]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Figs 1E, F, K</figureCitation>
)................................... (
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1881" box="[1342,1412,1545,1567]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Erotini">Erotini</taxonomicName>
) 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" box="[151,1436,1574,1596]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1574,1596]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
2. External elytral interstice with three rows of cells (Baltic amber)...................................... 
<emphasis box="[1320,1436,1574,1595]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Kolibaceum</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" box="[151,1436,1604,1626]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1604,1626]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
- External elytral interstice (lateriad of humeral costa) with two rows of cells (Baltic and 
<collectingRegion box="[1066,1130,1604,1625]" country="Ukraine" name="Rivne" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Rovno</collectingRegion>
amber)....... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1881" box="[1312,1436,1604,1625]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Helcophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1312,1436,1604,1625]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Helcophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
3. Elytral costa 3 robust in entire length; last elytral interstice wide, with irregular rows of cells (
<figureCitation box="[1126,1231,1633,1655]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Figs 1A–F</figureCitation>
) (
<collectingRegion box="[1250,1315,1633,1654]" country="Ukraine" name="Rivne" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Rovno</collectingRegion>
amber)..................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak, 2022" authorityName="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2022" box="[1226,1341,1663,1684]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Damzenium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1226,1341,1663,1684]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Damzenium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1346,1436,1662,1683]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1346,1436,1662,1683]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
- Elytral costa 3 weak, costa 4 robust in proximal half; last elytral interstice (lateriad of humeral costa) with one or two rows of cells (as in 
<figureCitation box="[334,408,1721,1743]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,184,1597]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[151,1436,181,1603]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A—J. Morphology of the extant Erotinae. A—Eropterus sp., Japan, general appearance, dorsal view; B–D— elytron, humeral part. B—Eropterus sp., Japan; C—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan; D—Lopheros sp., Japan. E— G—Pronotum. E—Eropterus trilineatus (Melsheimer), USA, dorsal view; F—Lopheros sp., Japan; G—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan. H– J General appearance, dorsal view. H—Helcophorus miniatus Fairmaire, Himalayas; I—Greenarus belokobylskyi Kazantsev, Vietnam; J—Laterialis sanguinea Kazantsev, China. Eocene Erotini. K—Protolopheros hoffeinsorum Kazantsev, Baltic amber (photo from Kazantsev, 2013). Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655708/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 2K</figureCitation>
)................................................................................... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
4. Median pronotal crest incomplete, obsolete in posterior half; lateral pronotal carinae do not reach median ridge (Baltic amber)..................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1940" box="[1256,1436,1780,1801]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudaplatopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1256,1436,1780,1801]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Pseudaplatopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1516,1860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
- Median pronotal crest complete; lateral pronotal carinae reach the median crest, supplied with short anterolateral carinae (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,184,1597]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[151,1436,181,1603]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A—J. Morphology of the extant Erotinae. A—Eropterus sp., Japan, general appearance, dorsal view; B–D— elytron, humeral part. B—Eropterus sp., Japan; C—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan; D—Lopheros sp., Japan. E— G—Pronotum. E—Eropterus trilineatus (Melsheimer), USA, dorsal view; F—Lopheros sp., Japan; G—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan. H– J General appearance, dorsal view. H—Helcophorus miniatus Fairmaire, Himalayas; I—Greenarus belokobylskyi Kazantsev, Vietnam; J—Laterialis sanguinea Kazantsev, China. Eocene Erotini. K—Protolopheros hoffeinsorum Kazantsev, Baltic amber (photo from Kazantsev, 2013). Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655708/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 2K</figureCitation>
) (Baltic amber)......................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kazantsev" authorityYear="2013" box="[1299,1436,1838,1859]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Protolopheros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1299,1436,1838,1859]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Protolopheros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
